{#
  Example 01 — Basic usage.

  The minimum viable control: a label and a slug list. The client.js
  resolves "medium" as the initial active size (since "medium" is in
  the list) and sets data-text-size="medium" on <html>.

  Drop the macro file alongside this one, the client.js next to that,
  and load the script tag at the bottom. The script is not optional:
  the macro renders an icon button plus a hidden listbox, and the
  button does not open until the client.js runs. See ../docs/ssr.md —
  that regression matters more here than in the sibling helpers,
  because this control exists to satisfy WCAG 1.4.4 (Resize Text).

  Note the status region below the control. The trigger is an
  icon-only button, so it never displays the active size, and a
  screen-reader user hears the active size only after opening the
  listbox. The status line is part of the default pattern — see
  ../docs/accessibility.md. Omitting it is the deliberate choice.
#}
{% from "../text-size-select.njk" import textSizeSelect %}

{{ textSizeSelect({
    label: "Text size",
    sizes: ["small", "medium", "large", "x-large"],
    storageKey: "lily-text-size"
}) }}

{#
  Visible by default: it helps sighted users and cognitive
  accessibility too, and WCAG 2.2 AAA favours it.

  aria-live="polite" announces mutations only, so this region is
  silent on first paint and speaks on each subsequent change.

  Because this line is itself page text, it visibly changes size when
  the user picks a new slug — immediate confirmation that the CSS
  below is actually wired up.
#}
<p class="text-size-select-status" aria-live="polite"></p>

{#
  The helper signals the choice; it defines no typography. THIS is the
  half that actually satisfies 1.4.4. Relative units only — absolute
  px would defeat both this control and the user's own browser
  settings.

  In a real project these rules belong in your stylesheet, not inline;
  they are here so the example stands alone.
#}
<style>
    :root,
    :root[data-text-size="medium"]  { --text-scale: 1; }
    :root[data-text-size="small"]   { --text-scale: 0.875; }
    :root[data-text-size="large"]   { --text-scale: 1.25; }
    :root[data-text-size="x-large"] { --text-scale: 1.5; }

    body { font-size: calc(1rem * var(--text-scale)); }
</style>

<script type="module">
    import { autoInit } from "../text-size-select.client.js";

    // Show the human label, not the raw slug. These strings are
    // consumer-supplied and translatable — the helper never hardcodes
    // user-facing text.
    const SIZE_LABELS = {
        small: "Small",
        medium: "Medium",
        large: "Large",
        "x-large": "Extra large",
    };
    const status = document.querySelector(".text-size-select-status");

    autoInit({
        onChange(slug) {
            status.textContent = `Text size: ${SIZE_LABELS[slug] ?? slug}`;
        },
    });
</script>
